quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
17,1,"Holy is He Who carried His servant by night from the Holy Mosque (in Makkah) to the farther Mosque (in Jerusalem) whose surroundings We have blessed that We might show him some of Our Signs. {1} Indeed He alone is All-Hearing, All-Seeing.",footnotes:1:The event referred to in this verse is known Miraj and Isra. According to authentic traditions
17,2,"We gave Moses the Book, and made it a source of guidance for the Children of Israel, {1} commanding: "Take no other Guardian beside Me." {2}",footnotes:1:As this verse has no apparent connection with the event of Miraj
17,3,"You are the descendants of those whom We carried (in the Ark) with Noah. {1} He was truly a thankful servant.",footnotes:1:That is
17,4,"Then We clearly declared to the Children of Israel in the Book: {1} "Twice you will make mischief in the land and will commit transgression." {2}",footnotes:1:The original Arabic word Al-kitab does not stand here for the Torah but for all the divine Books.Such warnings have been given in different Books of the Bible. As regards to their first mischief and its evil consequences
17,5,"So, when the occasion for the first of the transgressions arrived, We raised against you some of Our creatures who were full of might, and they ran over the whole of your land. This was a promise that was bound to be fulfilled. {1}",footnotes:1:This refers to the terrible destruction that the Israelites suffered at the hands of the Assyrians and Babylonians. One cannot fully appreciate the historical background of this merely from the extracts that have been reproduced above from the Books of the Prophets. A brief history of the Israelites is also needed so that a student may become acquainted with all the causes and circumstances on account of which Allah removed this nation
17,6,"Then We granted you an upper hand against them, and strengthened you with wealth and children, and multiplied your numbers. {1}",footnotes:1:This refers to the lease of time that the Israelites (That is the people of Judah) got after their release from the captivity of Babylon. As for the people of Israel and Samaria
17,7,"Whenever you did good, it was to your own advantage; and whenever you committed evil, it was to your own disadvantage. So, when the time of the fulfilment of the second promise arrived, (We raised other enemies that would) disfigure your faces and enter the Temple (of Jerusalem) as they had entered the first time, and destroy whatever they could lay their hands on. {1}",footnotes:1:The historical background of the second degeneration and its chastisement is as follows: The moral and religious fervor with which the Maccabees had started their movement gradually cooled down and was replaced by love of the world and empty external form. A split appeared among them and they themselves invited the Roman General
